ions by gold miners, and unscrupulous state interventions—Sanema are not merely prey. Predation, or appropriation without reciprocity, is essential to their own activities. They use predatory techniques of trickery in hunting and shamanism activities, while at the same time, they employ tactics of manipulation to obtain resources from neighbors and from the state. A richly detailed ethnography, Predatory Economies looks beyond well-worn tropes of activism and resistance to tell a new story of agency from an Indigenous perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGuaharibo IndiansxPolitical activityzVenezuela. 0aGuaharibo IndianszVenezuelaxEconomic conditions. 0aGuaharibo IndianszVenezuelaxSocial conditions. 0aGuaharibo IndianszVenezuelaxSocial life and customs. 0aNatural resourcesxSocial aspectszVenezuela. 0aPredation (Biology)xEconomic aspectszVenezuela. 0aPredation (Biology)xSocial aspectszVenezuela. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aSanema, Venezuela, extraction, oil extraction, Indigenous rights, Indigenous activism, gold, Indigenous peoples, Amazonian cosmology, shamanism, extractive economies, Yanomami.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32707440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477327098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/